{{infobox nebula |type= molecular cloud |name= Large Molecule Heimat |epoch= [[J2000.0]] <ref name="simbad">{{cite web|url=http://simbad.u-strasbg.fr/simbad/sim-id?Ident=NAME+LARGE+MOLECULE+HEIMAT|title=Large Molecule Heimat|accessdate=28 September 2015|author=Wenger|work=The SIMBAD astronomical database|display-authors=etal}}</ref> |ra= {{RA|17|47|20.0}} <ref name="simbad" /> |dec= {{DEC|-28|22|17}} <ref name="simbad" /> |constellation=[[Sagittarius (constellation)|Sagittarius]] |radius_ly=0.3<ref name="mpg"/> }}
The '''Large Molecule Heimat''' is a dense gas cloud located in the [[molecular cloud]] [[Sagittarius B2]].<ref name="mpg">{{cite web|url=http://www.mpg.de/567495/pressRelease20080325|accessdate=28 September 2015|date=26 March 2008|title=New organic molecules in space|publisher=Max Planck Society}}</ref> Many species of molecule, including [[aminoacetonitrile]] (a molecule related to [[glycine]]), [[ethyl formate]],<ref name="ras">{{cite web|url=https://www.ras.org.uk/search/article-archive/1609-ras-pn0925nam12two-highly-complex-organic-molecules-detected-in-space-|date=21 April 2009|accessdate=29 September 2015|title=Two highly complex organic molecules detected in space|publisher=[[Royal Astronomical Society]]}}</ref> and [[butyronitrile]],<ref name="ras" /> have been detected in the Large Molecule Heimat.<ref name="mpg" /><ref name="cordis">{{cite web|url=http://cordis.europa.eu/news/rcn/29274_en.html|title=Max Planck researchers identify new organic molecule in space|date=27 March 2008|accessdate=28 September 2015|publisher=Publications Office of the European Union|work=CORDIS}}</ref>
